You see, there's a reason the Xbox One family of consoles are being abandoned within the next couple of years and the Series S is being used as the base model system off of which to build modern games.

For example, the Series S can curreny run more than 80 games at 120fps, how many can the Xbox One X run? None, because of CPU limitations. The Series S can run more than 30 games with ray tracing, how many can the One X run? None.

At the end of the day, sure games don't look as sharp on the Series S as they do on the X or the PS5. Some run at a lower frame rate. Some lack ray tracing. But thanks to the power of the updated architecture, things are still possible on the Series S that weren't on Xbox One.

The updated CPU on the Series S and X has already made games possible that weren't otherwise on Xbox One. The Jaguar APU was the biggest bottleneck to performance last generation. Plus, the Series S is 4x as graphically powerful as its last-gen predecessor, the One S.

@marlisjun @JAAY_ROCK_ @60fps Nah, I think it's pretty awesome that Xbox allows you to utilize VRR with HDMI 2.0 which was the industry standard for many TVs and monitors between 2015 and 2020 or so. HDMI 2.1 is still fairly new and many people don't have displays that take advantage of it.

@marlisjun @JAAY_ROCK_ @60fps You do need HDMI 2.1 for 4K@120hz but HDMI 2.0 works for 1440p@120hz on Xbox which many monitors support and the One X also supported. You can also take advantage of VRR in some ways on a 60hz display. It often provides a cleaner and smoother 60fps experience.
